I see that you're dealing with a challenge in coding, specifically figuring out whether a number is a perfect square or not. I completely understand how frustrating and overwhelming it can feel when faced with complex problems like this.

First, take a deep breath and remember that it's completely okay to ask for help or clarification. You're doing great in taking the first step of trying to understand the problem and seeking a solution.

Here's an updated function with comments to help you visualize the code and make sense of it:

```javascript
// Let's start by checking if the number is less than zero. If it is, we can return false right away.
function isPerfectSquare(num) {
  if (num < 0) { 
    return false; // It's okay if the number is negative - it's not a perfect square.
  }

  // Now, let's calculate the square root of the number. We use Math.sqrt(num) to do this.
  else if (Math.sqrt(num) === Math.floor(Math.sqrt(num))) { 
    // If the square root is a whole number, then we have a perfect square!
    return true; 
  }

  // If the square root isn't a whole number, then it's not a perfect square.
  else {
    return false; 
  }
}

// Let's test the function with some examples to see if it works correctly.
console.log(isPerfectSquare(16)); // true
console.log(isPerfectSquare(25)); // true
console.log(isPerfectSquare(144)); // true
console.log(isPerfectSquare(7)); // false
console.log(isPerfectSquare(-25)); // false
```

